# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aggregate-data
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] In the statistical area of survival analysis, an **accelerated failure time model** (**AFT model**) is a parametric model that provides an alternative to the commonly used proportional hazards models.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Whereas a proportional hazards model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to multiply the hazard by some constant, an AFT model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to accelerate or decelerate the life course of a disease by some constant.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] There is strong basic science evidence from *C. elegans* experiments by Stroustrup et al. indicating that AFT models are the correct model for biological survival processes.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] where $\theta$ denotes the joint effect of covariates, typically $\theta =\exp(-[\beta _{1}X_{1}+\cdots +\beta _{p}X_{p}])$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] This is satisfied if the probability density function of the event is taken to be $f(t|\theta )=\theta f_{0}(\theta t)$ ; it then follows for the survival function that $S(t|\theta )=S_{0}(\theta t)$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] From this it is easy to see that the moderated life time T is distributed such that $T\theta$ and the unmoderated life time $T_{0}$ have the same distribution.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] where the last term is distributed as $\log(T_{0})$ , i.e., independently of $\theta$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] This reduces the accelerated failure time model to regression analysis (typically a linear model) where $-\log(\theta )$ represents the fixed effects, and $\epsilon$ represents the noise.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Different distributions of $\epsilon$ imply different distributions of $T_{0}$ , i.e., different baseline distributions of the survival time.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Typically, in survival-analytic contexts, many of the observations are censored: we only know that $T_{i}>t_{i}$ , not $T_{i}=t_{i}$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] In fact, the former case represents survival, while the later case represents an event/death/censoring during the follow-up.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] These right-censored observations can pose technical challenges for estimating the model, if the distribution of $T_{0}$ is unusual.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The interpretation of $\theta$ in accelerated failure time models is straightforward: $\theta =2$ means that everything in the relevant life history of an individual happens twice as fast.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, if the model concerns the development of a tumor, it means that all of the pre-stages progress twice as fast as for the unexposed individual, implying that the expected time until a clinical disease is 0.5 of the baseline time.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, this does not mean that the hazard function $\lambda (t|\theta )$ is always twice as high—that would be the proportional hazards model.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike proportional hazards models, in which Cox's semi-parametric proportional hazards model is more widely used than parametric models, AFT models are predominantly fully parametric i.e. a probability distribution is specified for $\log(T_{0})$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hence, technical developments in this direction would be highly desirable.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] When a frailty term is incorporated in the survival model, the regression parameter estimates from AFT models are robust to omitted covariates, unlike proportional hazards models.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] They are also less affected by the choice of probability distribution for the frailty term.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of AFT models are easily interpreted.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, the results of a clinical trial with mortality as the endpoint could be interpreted as a certain percentage increase in future life expectancy on the new treatment compared to the control.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] So a patient could be informed that he would be expected to live (say) 15% longer if he took the new treatment.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hazard ratios can prove harder to explain in layman's terms.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic distribution provides the most commonly used AFT model.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike the Weibull distribution, it can exhibit a non-monotonic hazard function which increases at early times and decreases at later times.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] It is somewhat similar in shape to the log-normal distribution but it has heavier tails.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic cumulative distribution function has a simple closed form, which becomes important computationally when fitting data with censoring.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] For the censored observations one needs the survival function, which is the complement of the cumulative distribution function, i.e. one needs to be able to evaluate $S(t|\theta )=1-F(t|\theta )$ .
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The Weibull distribution (including the exponential distribution as a special case) can be parameterised as either a proportional hazards model or an AFT model, and is the only family of distributions to have this property.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of fitting a Weibull model can therefore be interpreted in either framework.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, the biological applicability of this model may be limited by the fact that the hazard function is monotonic, i.e. either decreasing or increasing.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Any distribution on a multiplicatively closed group, such as the positive real numbers, is suitable for an AFT model.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Other distributions include the log-normal, gamma, hypertabastic, Gompertz distribution, and inverse Gaussian distributions, although they are less popular than the log-logistic, partly as their cumulative distribution functions do not have a closed form.
[src:aggregate-data/accelerated-failure-time-model] Finally, the generalized gamma distribution is a three-parameter distribution that includes the Weibull, log-normal and gamma distributions as special cases.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuaries are professionals trained in this discipline.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In many countries, actuaries must demonstrate their competence by passing a series of rigorous professional examinations focused in fields such as probability and predictive analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] News & World Report*, their job often has to do with using mathematics to identify risk so they can mitigate risk.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial science includes a number of interrelated subjects, including mathematics, probability theory, statistics, finance, economics, financial accounting and computer science.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Historically, actuarial science used deterministic models in the construction of tables and premiums.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The science has gone through revolutionary changes since the 1980s due to the proliferation of high speed computers and the union of stochastic actuarial models with modern financial theory.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Many universities have undergraduate and graduate degree programs in actuarial science.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In 2010, a study published by job search website CareerCast ranked actuary as the #1 job in the United States.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The study used five key criteria to rank jobs: environment, income, employment outlook, physical demands, and stress.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] News & World Report* ranked actuary as the third-best job in the business sector and the eighth-best job in STEM.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial science became a formal mathematical discipline in the late 17th century with the increased demand for long-term insurance coverage such as burial, life insurance, and annuities.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] These long term coverages required that money be set aside to pay future benefits, such as annuity and death benefits many years into the future.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] This requires estimating future contingent events, such as the rates of mortality by age, as well as the development of mathematical techniques for discounting the value of funds set aside and invested.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] This led to the development of an important actuarial concept, referred to as the present value of a future sum.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Certain aspects of the actuarial methods for discounting pension funds have come under criticism from modern financial economics.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial science is also applied to property, casualty, liability, and general insurance.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In these forms of insurance, coverage is generally provided on a renewable period (such as a yearly).
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Coverage can be cancelled at the end of the period by either party.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Property and casualty insurance companies tend to specialize because of the complexity and diversity of risks.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] One division is to organize around personal and commercial lines of insurance.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Personal lines of insurance are for individuals and include fire, auto, homeowners, theft, and umbrella coverages.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Commercial lines address the insurance needs of businesses and include property, business continuation, product liability, fleet/commercial vehicle, workers compensation, fidelity and surety, and D&O insurance.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The insurance industry also provides coverage for exposures such as catastrophe, weather-related risks, earthquakes, patent infringement and other forms of corporate espionage, terrorism, and "one-of-a-kind" (e.g., satellite launch).
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial science provides data collection, measurement, estimating, forecasting, and valuation tools to provide financial and underwriting data for management to assess marketing opportunities and the nature of the risks.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial science often helps to assess the overall risk from catastrophic events in relation to its underwriting capacity or surplus.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In the reinsurance fields, actuarial science can be used to design and price reinsurance and retrocession arrangements, and to establish reserve funds for known claims and future claims and catastrophes.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] There is an increasing trend to recognize that actuarial skills can be applied to a range of applications outside the traditional fields of insurance, pensions, etc.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] One notable example is the use in some US states of actuarial models to set criminal sentencing guidelines.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] These models attempt to predict the chance of re-offending according to rating factors which include the type of crime, age, educational background and ethnicity of the offender.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] However, these models have been open to criticism as providing justification for discrimination against specific ethnic groups by law enforcement personnel.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Whether this is statistically correct or a self-fulfilling correlation remains under debate.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Another example is the use of actuarial models to assess the risk of sex offense recidivism.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial models and associated tables, such as the MnSOST-R, Static-99, and SORAG, have been used since the late 1990s to determine the likelihood that a sex offender will re-offend and thus whether he or she should be institutionalized or set free.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Traditional actuarial science and modern financial economics in the US have different practices, which is caused by different ways of calculating funding and investment strategies, and by different regulations.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Historically, much of the foundation of actuarial theory predated modern financial theory.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In the early twentieth century, actuaries were developing many techniques that can be found in modern financial theory, but for various historical reasons, these developments did not achieve much recognition.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] As a result, actuarial science developed along a different path, becoming more reliant on assumptions, as opposed to the arbitrage-free risk-neutral valuation concepts used in modern finance.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The divergence is not related to the use of historical data and statistical projections of liability cash flows, but is instead caused by the manner in which traditional actuarial methods apply market data with those numbers.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] For example, one traditional actuarial method suggests that changing the mix of investments can change the value of liabilities and assets (by changing the discount rate assumption).
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] This concept is inconsistent with financial economics.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The potential of modern financial economics theory to complement existing actuarial science was recognized by actuaries in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, there was a distinct effort for actuaries to combine financial theory and stochastic methods into their established models.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Ideas from financial economics became increasingly influential in actuarial thinking, and actuarial science has started to embrace more sophisticated mathematical modelling of finance.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Today, the profession, both in practice and in the educational syllabi of many actuarial organizations, is cognizant of the need to reflect the combined approach of tables, loss models, stochastic methods, and financial theory.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] However, assumption-dependent concepts are still widely used (such as the setting of the discount rate assumption as mentioned earlier), particularly in North America.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Product design adds another dimension to the debate.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Financial economists argue that pension benefits are bond-like and should not be funded with equity investments without reflecting the risks of not achieving expected returns.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] But some pension products do reflect the risks of unexpected returns.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In some cases, the pension beneficiary assumes the risk, or the employer assumes the risk.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] 2. assets and liabilities with identical cash flows should have the same price.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] 3. the value of an asset is independent of its financing.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Essentially, financial economics state that pension assets should not be invested in equities for a variety of theoretical and practical reasons.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Elementary mutual aid agreements and pensions arose in antiquity.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Early in the Roman Empire, associations were formed to meet the expenses of burial, cremation, and monuments—precursors to burial insurance and friendly societies.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] A small sum was paid into a communal fund on a weekly basis, and upon the death of a member, the fund would cover the expenses of rites and burial.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] These societies sometimes sold shares in the building of columbāria, or burial vaults, owned by the fund—the precursor to mutual insurance companies.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Other early examples of mutual surety and assurance pacts can be traced back to various forms of fellowship within the Saxon clans of England and their Germanic forebears, and to Celtic society.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] However, many of these earlier forms of surety and aid would often fail due to lack of understanding and knowledge.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The 17th century was a period of advances in mathematics in Germany, France and England.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] At the same time there was a rapidly growing desire and need to place the valuation of personal risk on a more scientific basis.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Independently of each other, compound interest was studied and probability theory emerged as a well-understood mathematical discipline.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Another important advance came in 1662 from a London draper, the father of demography, John Graunt, who showed that there were predictable patterns of longevity and death in a group, or cohort, of people of the same age, despite the uncertainty of the date of death of any one individual.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] This study became the basis for the original life table.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] One could now set up an insurance scheme to provide life insurance or pensions for a group of people, and to calculate with some degree of accuracy how much each person in the group should contribute to a common fund assumed to earn a fixed rate of interest.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The first person to demonstrate publicly how this could be done was Edmond Halley (of Halley's Comet fame).
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Halley constructed his own life table, and showed how it could be used to calculate the premium amount someone of a given age should pay to purchase a life annuity.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] James Dodson's pioneering work on the long term insurance contracts under which the same premium is charged each year led to the formation of the Society for Equitable Assurances on Lives and Survivorship (now commonly known as Equitable Life) in London in 1762.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] William Morgan is often considered the father of modern actuarial science for his work in the field in the 1780s and 90s.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Many other life insurance companies and pension funds were created over the following 200 years.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Equitable Life was the first to use the word "actuary" for its chief executive officer in 1762.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Previously, "actuary" meant an official who recorded the decisions, or "acts", of ecclesiastical courts.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Other companies that did not use such mathematical and scientific methods most often failed or were forced to adopt the methods pioneered by Equitable.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In the 18th and 19th centuries, calculations were performed without computers.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuarial organizations were founded to support and further both actuaries and actuarial science, and to protect the public interest by promoting competency and ethical standards.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] However, calculations remained cumbersome, and actuarial shortcuts were commonplace.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Non-life actuaries followed in the footsteps of their life insurance colleagues during the 20th century.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The 1920 revision for the New-York based National Council on Workmen's Compensation Insurance rates took over two months of around-the-clock work by day and night teams of actuaries.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] In the 1930s and 1940s, the mathematical foundations for stochastic processes were developed.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] Actuaries could now begin to estimate losses using models of random events, instead of the deterministic methods they had used in the past.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] The introduction and development of the computer further revolutionized the actuarial profession.
[src:aggregate-data/actuarial-science] From pencil-and-paper to punchcards to current high-speed devices, the modeling and forecasting ability of the actuary has rapidly improved while still being heavily dependent on the assumptions input into the models; actuaries have needed to adjust to this new world.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In an **adaptive design** of a clinical trial, the parameters and conduct of the trial for a candidate drug or vaccine may be changed based on an interim analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Adaptive design typically involves advanced statistics to interpret a clinical trial endpoint.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] This is in contrast to traditional single-arm (i.e. non-randomized) clinical trials or randomized clinical trials (RCTs) that are static in their protocol and do not modify any parameters until the trial is completed.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The adaptation process takes place at certain points in the trial, prescribed in the trial protocol.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Importantly, this trial protocol is set before the trial begins with the adaptation schedule and processes specified.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Adaptions may include modifications to: dosage, sample size, drug undergoing trial, patient selection criteria and/or "cocktail" mix.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The PANDA (A Practical Adaptive & Novel Designs and Analysis toolkit) provides not only a summary of different adaptive designs, but also comprehensive information on adaptive design planning, conduct, analysis and reporting.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The aim of an adaptive trial is to more quickly identify drugs or devices that have a therapeutic effect, and to zero in on patient populations for whom the drug is appropriate.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] When conducted efficiently, adaptive trials have the potential to find new treatments while minimizing the number of patients exposed to the risks of clinical trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Specifically, adaptive trials can efficiently discover new treatments by reducing the number of patients enrolled in treatment groups that show minimal efficacy or higher adverse-event rates.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Adaptive trials can adjust almost any part of its design, based on pre-set rules and statistical design, such as sample size, adding new groups, dropping less effective groups and changing the probability of being randomized to a particular group, for example.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In 2004, a Strategic Path Initiative was introduced by the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to modify the way drugs travel from lab to market.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] This initiative aimed at dealing with the high attrition levels observed in the clinical phase.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] It also attempted to offer flexibility to investigators to find the optimal clinical benefit without affecting the study's validity.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Adaptive clinical trials initially came under this regime.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The FDA issued draft guidance on adaptive trial design in 2010.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] By 2019, the FDA updated their 2010 recommendations and issued "Adaptive Design Clinical Trials for Drugs and Biologics Guidance".
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In October of 2021, the FDA Center for Veterinary Medicine issued the Guidance Document "Adaptive and Other Innovative Designs for Effectiveness Studies of New Animal Drugs".
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The trial is conducted as prescribed by the design.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Once the data are ready, they are analysed according to a pre-specified analysis plan.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Any trial design that can change its design, during active enrollment, could be considered an adaptive clinical trial.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] There are a number of different types, and real life trials may combine elements from these different trial types: In some cases, trials have become an ongoing process that regularly adds and drops therapies and patient groups as more information is gained.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Phase I of clinical research focuses on selecting a particular dose of a drug to carry forward into future trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Historically, such trials have had a "rules-based" (or "algorithm-based") design, such as the 3+3 design.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] However, these "A+B" rules-based designs are not appropriate for phase I studies and are inferior to adaptive, model-based designs.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] An example of a superior design is the continual reassessment method (CRM).
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Group sequential design is the application of sequential analysis to clinical trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] At each interim analysis, investigators will use the current data to decide whether the trial should either stop or should continue to recruit more participants.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The trial might stop either because the evidence that the treatment is working is strong ("stopping for benefit") or weak ("stopping for futility").
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Whether a trial may stop for futility only, benefit only, or either, is stated in advance.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] A design has "binding stopping rules" when the trial must stop when a particular threshold of (either strong or weak) evidence is crossed at a particular interim analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Otherwise it has "non-binding stopping rules", in which case other information can be taken into account, for example safety data.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The number of interim analyses is specified in advance, and can be anything from a single interim analysis (a "two-stage" design") to an interim analysis after every participant ("continuous monitoring").
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] For trials with a binary (response/no response) outcome and a single treatment arm, a popular and simple group sequential design with two stages is the Simon design.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In this design, there is a single interim analysis partway through the trial, at which point the trial either stops for futility or continues to the second stage.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Mander and Thomson also proposed a design with a single interim analysis, at which point the trial could stop for either futility or benefit.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] For single-arm, single-stage binary outcome trials, a trial's success or failure is determined by the number of responses observed by the end of the trial.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] This means that it may be possible to know the conclusion of the trial (success or failure) with certainty before all the data are available.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Planning to stop a trial once the conclusion is known with certainty is called *non-stochastic curtailment*.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] This reduces the sample size on average.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Planning to stop a trial when the probability of success, based on the results so far, is either above or below a certain threshold is called *stochastic curtailment*.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] This reduces the average sample size even more than non-stochastic curtailment.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Stochastic and non-stochastic curtailment can also be used in two-arm binary outcome trials, where a trial's success or failure is determined by the number of responses observed on each arm by the end of the trial.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The adaptive design method developed mainly in the early 21st century.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In November 2019, the US Food and Drug Administration provided guidelines for using adaptive designs in clinical trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In April 2020, the World Health Organization published an "R&D Blueprint (for the) novel Coronavirus" (Blueprint).
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The WHO vaccine coalition prioritized which vaccines would go into Phase II and III clinical trials, and determined harmonized Phase III protocols for all vaccines achieving the pivotal trial stage.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The global "Solidarity" and European "Discovery" trials of hospitalized people with severe COVID‑19 infection applied adaptive design to rapidly alter trial parameters as results from the four experimental therapeutic strategies emerge.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The US National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) initiated an adaptive design, international Phase III trial (called "ACTT") to involve up to 800 hospitalized COVID‑19 people at 100 sites in multiple countries.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] An adaptive trial design enabled two experimental breast cancer drugs to deliver promising results after just six months of testing, far shorter than usual.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Researchers assessed the results while the trial was in process and found that cancer had been eradicated in more than half of one group of patients.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The trial, known as I-Spy 2, tested 12 experimental drugs.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] For its predecessor I-SPY 1, 10 cancer centers and the National Cancer Institute (NCI SPORE program and the NCI Cooperative groups) collaborated to identify response indicators that would best predict survival for women with high-risk breast cancer.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] During 2002–2006, the study monitored 237 patients undergoing neoadjuvant therapy before surgery.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Iterative MRI and tissue samples monitored the biology of patients to chemotherapy given in a neoadjuvant setting, or presurgical setting.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Evaluating chemotherapy's direct impact on tumor tissue took much less time than monitoring outcomes in thousands of patients over long time periods.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The approach helped to standardize the imaging and tumor sampling processes, and led to miniaturized assays.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Key findings included that tumor response was a good predictor of patient survival, and that tumor shrinkage during treatment was a good predictor of long-term outcome.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Importantly, the vast majority of tumors identified as high risk by molecular signature.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] However, heterogeneity within this group of women and measuring response within tumor subtypes was more informative than viewing the group as a whole.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Within genetic signatures, level of response to treatment appears to be a reasonable predictor of outcome.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Additionally, its shared database has furthered the understanding of drug response and generated new targets and agents for subsequent testing.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] I-SPY 2 is an adaptive clinical trial of multiple Phase 2 treatment regimens combined with standard chemotherapy.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] I-SPY 2 linked 19 academic cancer centers, two community centers, the FDA, the NCI, pharmaceutical and biotech companies, patient advocates and philanthropic partners.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The trial is sponsored by the Biomarker Consortium of the Foundation for the NIH (FNIH), and is co-managed by the FNIH and QuantumLeap Healthcare Collaborative.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] I-SPY 2 was designed to explore the hypothesis that different combinations of cancer therapies have varying degrees of success for different patients.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Conventional clinical trials that evaluate post-surgical tumor response require a separate trial with long intervals and large populations to test each combination.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Instead, I-SPY 2 is organized as a continuous process.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] It efficiently evaluates multiple therapy regimes by relying on the predictors developed in I-SPY 1 that help quickly determine whether patients with a particular genetic signature will respond to a given treatment regime.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The trial is adaptive in that the investigators learn as they go, and do not continue treatments that appear to be ineffective.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] All patients are categorized based on tissue and imaging markers collected early and iteratively (a patient's markers may change over time) throughout the trial, so that early insights can guide treatments for later patients.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Treatments that show positive effects for a patient group can be ushered to confirmatory clinical trials, while those that do not can be rapidly sidelined.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Importantly, confirmatory trials can serve as a pathway for FDA Accelerated Approval.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] I-SPY 2 can simultaneously evaluate candidates developed by multiple companies, escalating or eliminating drugs based on immediate results.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Using a single standard arm for comparison for all candidates in the trial saves significant costs over individual Phase 3 trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] All data are shared across the industry.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] As of January 2016 I-SPY 2 is comparing 11 new treatments against 'standard therapy', and is estimated to complete in Sept 2017.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] By mid 2016 several treatments had been selected for later stage trials.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Researchers under the EPAD project by the Innovative Medicines Initiative are utilizing an adaptive trial design to help speed development of Alzheimer's disease treatments, with a budget of 53 million euros.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The first trial under the initiative was expected to begin in 2015 and to involve about a dozen companies.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] As of 2020, 2,000 people over the age of 50 have been recruited across Europe for a long term study on the earliest stages of Alzheimer's.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The EPAD project plans to use the results from this study and other data to inform 1,500 person selected adaptive clinical trials of drugs to prevent Alzheimer's.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The adjustable nature of adaptive trials inherently suggests the use of Bayesian statistical analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Bayesian statistics inherently address updating information such as that seen in adaptive trials that change from updated information derived from interim analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The problem of adaptive clinical trial design is more or less exactly the bandit problem as studied in the field of reinforcement learning.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The Bayesian framework Continuous Individualized Risk Index which is based on dynamic measurements from cancer patients can be effectively used for adaptive trial designs.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Platform trials rely heavily on Bayesian designs.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] For regulatory submission of Bayesian clinical trial design, there exist two Bayesian decision rules that are frequently used by trial sponsors.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In most regulatory submissions, Bayesian trial designs are calibrated to possess good frequentist properties.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In this spirit, and in adherence to regulatory practice, regulatory agencies typically recommend that sponsors provide the frequentist type I and II error rates for the sponsor's proposed Bayesian analysis plan.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In other words, the Bayesian designs for the regulatory submission need to satisfy the type I and II error requirement in most cases in the frequentist sense.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Some exception may happen in the context of external data borrowing where the type I error rate requirement can be relaxed to some degree depending on the confidence of the historical information.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] The logistics of managing traditional, non-adaptive design clinical trials may be complex.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] In adaptive design clinical trials, adapting the design as results arrive adds to the complexity of design, monitoring, drug supply, data capture and randomization.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Furthermore, it should be stated in the trial's protocol exactly what kind of adaptation will be permitted.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Publishing the trial protocol in advance increases the validity of the final results, as it makes clear that any adaptation that took place during the trial was planned, rather than ad hoc.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] According to PCAST "One approach is to focus studies on specific subsets of patients most likely to benefit, identified based on validated biomarkers.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Adaptive designs have added statistical complexity compared to traditional clinical trial designs.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] For example, any multiple testing, either from looking at multiple treatment arms or from looking at a single treatment arm multiple times, must be accounted for.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Another example is statistical bias, which can be more likely when using adaptive designs, and again must be accounted for.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] While an adaptive design may be an improvement over a non-adaptive design in some respects (for example, expected sample size), it is not always the case that an adaptive design is a better choice overall: in some cases, the added complexity of the adaptive design may not justify its benefits.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] An example of this is when the trial is based on a measurement that takes a long time to observe, as this would mean having an interim analysis when many participants have started treatment but cannot yet contribute to the interim results.
[src:aggregate-data/adaptive-clinical-trial] Shorter trials may not reveal longer term risks, such as a cancer's return.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] An **aggregate** is a type of summary used in dimensional models of data warehouses to shorten the time it takes to provide answers to typical queries on large sets of data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] The reason why aggregates can make such a dramatic increase in the performance of a data warehouse is the reduction of the number of rows to be accessed when responding to a query.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] In its simplest form, an **aggregate** is a simple summary table that can be derived by performing a *Group by* SQL query.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] A more common use of aggregates is to take a dimension and change its granularity.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] When changing the granularity of the dimension the fact table has to be partially summarized to fit the new grain of the new dimension, thus creating new dimensional and fact tables, to fit this new level of grain.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] Aggregates are sometimes referred to as pre-calculated summary data, since aggregations are usually precomputed, partially summarized data, that are stored in new aggregated tables.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] When facts are aggregated, it is either done by eliminating dimensionality or by associating the facts with a rolled up dimension.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] Rolled up dimensions should be shrunken versions of the dimensions associated with the granular base facts.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] This way, the aggregated dimension tables should conform to the base dimension tables.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] Having aggregates and atomic data increases the complexity of the dimensional model.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] This complexity should be transparent to the users of the data warehouse, thus when a request is made, the data warehouse should return data from the table with the correct grain.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] So when requests to the data warehouse are made, aggregate navigator functionality should be implemented, to help determine the correct table with the correct grain.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] Since it would produce a lot of overhead to build all possible aggregations, it is a good idea to choose a subset of tables on which to make aggregations.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] The best way to choose this subset and decide which aggregations to build is to monitor queries and design aggregations to match query patterns.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] Having aggregate data in the dimensional model makes the environment more complex.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] To make this extra complexity transparent to the user, functionality known as aggregate navigation is used to query the dimensional and fact tables with the correct grain level.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data-warehouse] The aggregate navigation essentially examines the query to see if it can be answered using a smaller, aggregate table.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] There is a distinction between aggregate data and individual data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data refers to individual data that are averaged by geographic area, by year, by service agency, or by other means.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Individual data are disaggregated individual results and are used to conduct analyses for estimation of subgroup differences.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are mainly used by researchers and analysts, policymakers, banks and administrators for multiple reasons.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] They are used to evaluate policies, recognise trends and patterns of processes, gain relevant insights, and assess current measures for strategic planning.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data collected from various sources are used in different areas of studies such as comparative political analysis and APD scientific analysis for further analyses.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are also used for medical and educational purposes.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data is widely used, but it also has some limitations, including drawing inaccurate inferences and false conclusions which is also termed 'ecological fallacy'.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] 'Ecological fallacy' means that it is invalid for users to draw conclusions on the ecological relationships between two quantitative variables at the individual level.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In statistics, **aggregate data** are data combined from several measurements.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] When data is aggregated, groups of observations are replaced with summary statistics based on those observations.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In a data warehouse, the use of aggregate data dramatically reduces the time to query large sets of data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Developers pre-summarise queries that are regularly used, such as Weekly Sales across several dimensions for example by item hierarchy or geographical hierarchy.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Researchers use aggregate data to understand the prevalent ethos, evaluate the essence of social realities and a social organisation, stipulate primary issues of concern in research, and supply projections in relation to the nature of social issues.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are useful for researchers when they are interested in investigating on the relationships between two distinct variables at the aggregate level, and the connections between an aggregate variable and a characteristic at the individual level.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Researchers have also made an effort to evaluate policies, practices and precepts of systems critically with the assistance of aggregate data, to investigate the corresponding relevance and efficacy.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are used by governments to develop more effective policies because they serve as a measure of how capable a government is to be aware of the demands and needs of its citizens and a measure of the way a government maintains social order effectively.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] For example, governments around the world use of aggregate mobile location data for analysis in response to Covid-19.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate mobile location data could provide insights about the effectiveness of social distancing measures launched by governments.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Governments also use aggregate data to identify possible "hot spots" and the potential for transmission.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Policymakers also utilise financial aggregates data in evaluating companies and households' economic and financial activities because these data help to identify risks associated with financial stability.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Policymakers can employ aggregate data to better understand the developments of a country's economic and financial conditions.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Banks collect aggregated data from a significant number of customers and then anonymise the data through eliminating personal information.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The main reason for banks to use aggregate data is to estimate economic trends and gain insights on customer clusters.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Banks are not permitted to share customers' personal data, but aggregate data can be shared with banks' business customers and can be accessed by other partners who also use the same platform to acquire information on aggregate data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In Australia, the Commonwealth Bank provides its business clients anonymised data related to their customers which are derived from card transactions.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The ANZ also provides its business customers with anonymised data which is gathered from millions of merchant terminal transactions and ANZ card transactions.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In the UK, the Integrated Urgent Care Aggregate Data Collection (IUC ADC) provides comprehensive information about IUC activity, its performance, as well as its service demand.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Its data are sourced from the lead data providers responsible for offering integrated urgent care services in England.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The National Health Service (NHS) under the Department of Health and Social Care (DHSC) in England stated that this collection of aggregate data is going to replace the NHS 111 minimum dataset.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] It will also be used as a formal source for IUC statistics, as well as to oversee the Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) of the IUC ADC.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] National or regional level of available empirical data are used by administrators and intellectuals, as well as people who are concerned about a region or a society's welfare, as sources of reference.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In particular, administrators utilise aggregate data for assessments in current political, religious, social, or other atmosphere of a nation to track the gaps in social responses relating to time and space, and to dictate priorities for action.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] These assessments help administrators in evaluating current measures that are useful in future strategic planning and provide indicators about effective corrective measures.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data can be a composition of various types of writings and records, including biography, autobiography, descriptive accounts and correspondence.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] For example, a researcher collects, collates, or compiles aggregate data through utilising multiple mechanisms of social research, including inventory, interview, an opinionnaire, and a questionnaire or schedule.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Official or non-official agencies also collect and compile aggregate data on an ongoing basis through utilising infrastructures available within a department at the field level.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Sources of aggregate data can also be regarded as tools for discovering data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In the US, some of the US data are presented in the form of tables.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Examples of sources for these US aggregate data include the United States Census Bureau, Statistical Abstract of the United States, and Social Explorer.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] International Monetary Fund data, World DataBank, and Penn World Table are examples of transactional and international aggregate data sources.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data is used in comparative political analysis because analysts do not only focus on individual's behaviour.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] They also focus on the behaviour of areal units, including electoral constituencies and nations.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In political activity analyses, significant data such as those related to industrialisation, urbanization, as well as mass communication networks, are not expressed readily in individual levels.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] They are expressed in per capita terms in order to control for the variations in the areal units' population size.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are widely available because demographic, socio-economic, and political data are collected and published by the nations.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] This facilitates researchers and analysts in carrying out longer trend studies and allows them to bring changes and developments in a deeper focus.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Factors including the need for time, considerable resources and wide international cooperation, impeded the use of individual patient data (IPD) meta-analysis, which led to most of the published meta-analyses relying upon aggregate patient data (APD).
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] To acquire data in all trials on all patients, aggregate patient data are collected from completed studies being presented at professional meetings, published in the medical literature, or were directly supplied by individual investigators.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The aggregated patient data are utilised by users including the Cochrane Collaboration, the United States Preventive Services Task Force, and multiple professional societies in providing support for clinical practice guidelines.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate patient data are also used in time-to-event studies of meta-analyses as the results can inform investors about the worthiness to proceed to conducting more meta-analyses that are based on resource-intensive individual patient data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In a health information system, aggregate data is the integration of data concerning numerous patients.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] A particular patient cannot be traced based on aggregate data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] These aggregated data are only counts, including Tuberculous, Malaria, or other diseases.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Health facilities use this type of aggregated statistics to generate reports and indicators, and to undertake strategic planning in their health systems.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Compared with aggregated data, patient data are individual data related to a single patient, including one's name, age, diagnosis and medical history.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Patient-based data are mainly used to track the progress of a patient, such as how the patient responds to particular treatment, over time.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The COVID-19 Data Archive, also called the COVID-ARC, aggregates data from studies around the globe.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Researchers are able to have access towards the discoveries of international colleagues and forges collaborations to facilitate processes involved in fighting against the disease.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Specifically, using aggregated healthcare data allows health care providers to unbolt actionable clinical insights when for instance, thorough views of clinical data or continuous patient records become possible.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data such as aggregate school-level demographic data and aggregate school-level achievement data are used in experimental analysis to assess the relationships between student achievement and school-level interventions.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data can also be used in non-experimental analysis such as regression discontinuity analysis and interrupted time-series analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Individual-level data are not required in these non-experimental analyses.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] For example, interrupted time-series analysis estimates the impact brought by a school-level program through comparing a school's achievement before and after the program is launched where individual-level data are not necessary.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] During the process of averaging units within some cluster or within a country, information is lost which increases the probability of drawing inaccurate inferences.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Information loss occurs because aggregation of data ignores individual variation as if it were only a type of statistical noise or measurement error.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Inference also vary from one to another when either individual firm data or aggregated data is used for analysis.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] For instance, calculation of country averages does not account for firm-specific variables, such as firm size, firm age, or firm-ownership concentration, but calculation of individual averages does.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Differences exist between results generated from aggregate data and individual data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] There is also a problem of 'ecological fallacy'.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The concept was brought about by Robinson (1950).
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The meaning of the term is that the variability around the individual-level means is significantly different from the variability encompassing the aggregate means.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] With the aggregate concept, things other than the individual equivalents of aggregate data are expressed, which means that individual-level conclusions cannot be drawn.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Although aggregate data has wider applicability than individual-level data, it is more challenging for researchers to tackle with analysis on subgroup results when aggregate data is used.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Eventually, individual information may also be required.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Growth modelling and longitudinal modelling based on aggregate data are also difficult because variables can vary over time.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Financial aggregates data is a type of aggregate data about credit and the money supply in Australia, which is utilised by policymakers in evaluating both the households and the companies' economic and financial activities.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Credit aggregates are measurements of the households and businesses' borrowings from financial intermediaries.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The amount of funds borrowed by businesses for purposes including project investments, assets purchases, or cash flow managements are also measured using credit aggregates.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Monetary aggregates are measurements of the money or 'money-like' instruments of the banking system, which is owed to businesses and households.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] An example of a 'money-like' instrument is deposits in the bank account.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] In the UK, census aggregate data are data generated as outputs from the United Kingdom censuses.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] They provide information about the socio-economic and demographic characteristics of the country's population.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Aggregate data are used as components of the UK censuses' outputs.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] They are obtained from analysis on the information given in the census returns.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] The census aggregate data are used to compare and describe population characteristics across various locations in the UK because they are able to provide comparable information at a range of geographical levels over the entire UK.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-data] Census aggregate data are also utilised in the academic sector for teaching and research purposes, as well as for site location and marketing in the private sector.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] In database management, an **aggregate function** or **aggregation function** is a function where multiple values are processed together to form a single summary statistic.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Formally, an aggregate function takes as input a set, a multiset (bag), or a list from some input domain *I* and outputs an element of an output domain *O*.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] The input and output domains may be the same, such as for `SUM`, or may be different, such as for `COUNT`.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Aggregate functions occur commonly in numerous programming languages, in spreadsheets, and in relational algebra.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] The `listagg` function, as defined in the SQL:2016 standard aggregates data from multiple rows into a single concatenated string.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] In the entity relationship diagram, aggregation is represented as seen in Figure 1 with a rectangle around the relationship and its entities to indicate that it is being treated as an aggregate entity.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Aggregate functions present a bottleneck, because they potentially require having all input values at once.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] In distributed computing, it is desirable to divide such computations into smaller pieces, and distribute the work, usually computing in parallel, via a divide and conquer algorithm.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Some aggregate functions can be computed by computing the aggregate for subsets, and then aggregating these aggregates; examples include COUNT, MAX, MIN, and SUM.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] In other cases the aggregate cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be distributed; examples include DISTINCT COUNT (Count-distinct problem), MEDIAN, and MODE.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Such functions are called **decomposable aggregation functions** or **decomposable aggregate functions**.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] where ⁠ $\uplus$ ⁠ is the union of multisets (see monoid homomorphism).
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Note that self-decomposable aggregation functions can be combined (formally, taking the product) by applying them separately, so for instance one can compute both the SUM and COUNT at the same time, by tracking two numbers.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] More generally, one can define a **decomposable aggregation function** f as one that can be expressed as the composition of a final function g and a self-decomposable aggregation function h, $f=g\circ h,f(X)=g(h(X))$ .
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] For example, AVERAGE=SUM/COUNT and RANGE=MAX−MIN.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] Decomposable aggregation functions are important in online analytical processing (OLAP), as they allow aggregation queries to be computed on the pre-computed results in the OLAP cube, rather than on the base data.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] For example, it is easy to support COUNT, MAX, MIN, and SUM in OLAP, since these can be computed for each cell of the OLAP cube and then summarized ("rolled up"), but it is difficult to support MEDIAN, as that must be computed for every view separately.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregate-function] In order to calculate the average and standard deviation from aggregate data, it is necessary to have available for each group: the total of values (Σxi = SUM(x)), the number of values (N=COUNT(x)) and the total of squares of the values (Σxi2=SUM(x2)) of each groups.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] AIQ was founded in 2013 by Zack Massingham, a former university administrator and Jeff Silvester.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] As of February 2017, AIQ employed 20 people and was based in downtown Victoria, British Columbia.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] AIQ has attracted controversy over its involvement in the Vote Leave and BeLeave campaigns in 2016 and the Cambridge Analytica scandal that broke out in 2018.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] Under UK law, co-ordination between groups during an election is prohibited.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] In May 2018, a Facebook executive testified before the House of Commons Select Committee for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport that Vote Leave and BeLeave were targeting exactly the same audiences on Facebook via AIQ.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] Prior to the Brexit campaign, AIQ had worked with John Bolton before he became Donald Trump's national security adviser, and with US senators Thom Tillis and Ted Cruz on their senatorial campaigns.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] As part of Cambridge Analytica's work for the Cruz campaign, AIQ created Ripon, a customized campaign software platform that became the prototype used by pro-Brexit campaign groups, including VoteLeave and BeLeave.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] On 6 April 2018, Facebook suspended AggregateIQ from its platform due to concerns over its possible affiliation with SCL Group, the parent company of Cambridge Analytica.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] On 20 September 2018, AggregateIQ became the first company to be served a formal notice by the UK's Information Commissioner's Office for breaching the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] The company has launched an appeal against the notice.
[src:aggregate-data/aggregateiq] AIQ has also been reprimanded by the Privacy Commissioner of Canada and the Privacy Commissioner of British Columbia, who stated in a report issued in November 2019 that the company had violated privacy laws in its handling of British voters' data during the Vote Leave campaign.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The **Akaike information criterion** (**AIC**) is an estimator of prediction error and thereby relative quality of statistical models for a given set of data.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Given a collection of models for the data, AIC estimates the quality of each model, relative to each of the other models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Thus, AIC provides a means for model selection.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] When a statistical model is used to represent the process that generated the data, the representation will almost never be exact; so some information will be lost by using the model to represent the process.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] AIC estimates the relative amount of information lost by a given model: the less information a model loses, the higher the quality of that model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In estimating the amount of information lost by a model, AIC deals with the trade-off between the goodness of fit of the model and the simplicity of the model, balancing the risk of overfitting with the risk of underfitting.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The Akaike information criterion is named after the Japanese statistician Hirotugu Akaike, who formulated it.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] It now forms the basis of a paradigm for the foundations of statistics and is also widely used for statistical inference.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Suppose that we have a statistical model of some data.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let *k* be the number of estimated parameters in the model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let ${\hat {L}}$ be the maximized value of the likelihood function for the model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Then the AIC value of the model is the following.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Given a set of candidate models for the data, the preferred model is the one with the minimum AIC value.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Thus, AIC rewards goodness of fit (as assessed by the likelihood function), but it also includes a penalty that is an increasing function of the number of estimated parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The penalty discourages overfitting, which is desired because increasing the number of parameters in the model almost always improves the goodness of the fit.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Suppose that the data is generated by some unknown process *f*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We consider two candidate models to represent *f*: *g*1 and *g*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] If we knew *f*, then we could find the information lost from using *g*1 to represent *f* by calculating the Kullback–Leibler divergence, *D*KL(*f* ‖ *g*1); similarly, the information lost from using *g*2 to represent *f* could be found by calculating *D*KL(*f* ‖ *g*2).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We would then, generally, choose the candidate model that minimized the information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We cannot choose with certainty, because we do not know *f*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Akaike (1974) showed, however, that we can estimate, via AIC, how much more (or less) information is lost by *g*1 than by *g*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The estimate, though, is only valid asymptotically; if the number of data points is small, then some correction is often necessary (see AICc, below).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that AIC tells nothing about the absolute quality of a model, only the quality relative to other models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Thus, if all the candidate models fit poorly, AIC will not give any warning of that.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Hence, after selecting a model via AIC, it is usually good practice to validate the absolute quality of the model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Such validation commonly includes checks of the model's residuals (to determine whether the residuals seem random) and tests of the model's predictions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For more on this topic, see *statistical model validation*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To apply AIC in practice, we start with a set of candidate models, and then find the models' corresponding AIC values.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] There will almost always be information lost due to using a candidate model to represent the "true model," i.e. the process that generated the data.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We wish to select, from among the candidate models, the model that minimizes the information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We cannot choose with certainty, but we can minimize the estimated information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Suppose that there are *R* candidate models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Denote the AIC values of those models by AIC1, AIC2, AIC3, ..., AIC*R*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let AICmin be the minimum of those values.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Then the quantity exp((AICmin − AIC*i*)/2) can be interpreted as being proportional to the probability that the *i*th model minimizes the (estimated) information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] As an example, suppose that there are three candidate models, whose AIC values are 100, 102, and 110.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Then the second model is exp((100 − 102)/2) = 0.368 times as probable as the first model to minimize the information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Similarly, the third model is exp((100 − 110)/2) = 0.007 times as probable as the first model to minimize the information loss.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In this example, we would omit the third model from further consideration.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The quantity exp((AICmin − AIC*i*)/2) is known as the *relative likelihood* of model *i*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] It is closely related to the likelihood ratio used in the likelihood-ratio test.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Indeed, if all the models in the candidate set have the same number of parameters, then using AIC might at first appear to be very similar to using the likelihood-ratio test.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] There are, however, important distinctions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In particular, the likelihood-ratio test is valid only for nested models, whereas AIC (and AICc) has no such restriction.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Every statistical hypothesis test can be formulated as a comparison of statistical models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Hence, every statistical hypothesis test can be replicated via AIC.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Two examples are briefly described in the subsections below.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Details for those examples, and many more examples, are given by Sakamoto, Ishiguro & Kitagawa (1986, Part II) and Konishi & Kitagawa (2008, ch.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] As an example of a hypothesis test, consider the *t*-test to compare the means of two normally-distributed populations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The input to the *t*-test comprises a random sample from each of the two populations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To formulate the test as a comparison of models, we construct two different models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The first model models the two populations as having potentially different means and standard deviations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The likelihood function for the first model is thus the product of the likelihoods for two distinct normal distributions; so it has four parameters: *μ*1, *σ*1, *μ*2, *σ*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To be explicit, the likelihood function is as follows (denoting the sample sizes by *n*1 and *n*2).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The second model models the two populations as having the same means and the same standard deviations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The likelihood function for the second model thus sets *μ*1 = *μ*2 and *σ*1 = *σ*2 in the above equation; so it only has two parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We then maximize the likelihood functions for the two models (in practice, we maximize the log-likelihood functions); after that, it is easy to calculate the AIC values of the models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We next calculate the relative likelihood.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For instance, if the second model was only 0.01 times as likely as the first model, then we would omit the second model from further consideration: so we would conclude that the two populations have different means.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The *t*-test assumes that the two populations have identical standard deviations; the test tends to be unreliable if the assumption is false and the sizes of the two samples are very different (Welch's *t*-test would be better).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Comparing the means of the populations via AIC, as in the example above, has the same disadvantage.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] However, one could create a third model that allows different standard deviations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] This third model would have the advantage of not making such assumptions at the cost of an additional parameter and thus degree of freedom.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For another example of a hypothesis test, suppose that we have two populations, and each member of each population is in one of two categories—category #1 or category #2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Each population is binomially distributed.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We want to know whether the distributions of the two populations are the same.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We are given a random sample from each of the two populations.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let *m* be the size of the sample from the first population.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let *m*1 be the number of observations (in the sample) in category #1; so the number of observations in category #2 is *m* − *m*1.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Similarly, let *n* be the size of the sample from the second population.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let *n*1 be the number of observations (in the sample) in category #1.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let p be the probability that a randomly-chosen member of the first population is in category #1.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Hence, the probability that a randomly-chosen member of the first population is in category #2 is 1 − *p*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that the distribution of the first population has one parameter.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Let q be the probability that a randomly-chosen member of the second population is in category #1.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that the distribution of the second population also has one parameter.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To compare the distributions of the two populations, we construct two different models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The first model models the two populations as having potentially different distributions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The likelihood function for the first model is thus the product of the likelihoods for two distinct binomial distributions; so it has two parameters: p, q.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To be explicit, the likelihood function is as follows.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The second model models the two populations as having the same distribution.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The likelihood function for the second model thus sets *p* = *q* in the above equation; so the second model has one parameter.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For instance, if the second model was only 0.01 times as likely as the first model, then we would omit the second model from further consideration: so we would conclude that the two populations have different distributions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Statistical inference is generally regarded as comprising hypothesis testing and estimation.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Hypothesis testing can be done via AIC, as discussed above.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Regarding estimation, there are two types: point estimation and interval estimation.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Point estimation can be done within the AIC paradigm: it is provided by maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Interval estimation can also be done within the AIC paradigm: it is provided by likelihood intervals.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Hence, statistical inference generally can be done within the AIC paradigm.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The most commonly used paradigms for statistical inference are frequentist inference and Bayesian inference.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] AIC, though, can be used to do statistical inference without relying on either the frequentist paradigm or the Bayesian paradigm: because AIC can be interpreted without the aid of significance levels or Bayesian priors.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In other words, AIC can be used to form a foundation of statistics that is distinct from both frequentism and Bayesianism.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] When the sample size is small, there is a substantial probability that AIC will select models that have too many parameters, i.e. that AIC will overfit.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To address such potential overfitting, AICc was developed: AICc is AIC with a correction for small sample sizes.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The formula for AICc depends upon the statistical model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Assuming that the model is univariate, is linear in its parameters, and has normally-distributed residuals (conditional upon regressors), then the formula for AICc is as follows.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] —where *n* denotes the sample size and *k* denotes the number of parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Thus, AICc is essentially AIC with an extra penalty term for the number of parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that as *n* → ∞, the extra penalty term converges to 0, and thus AICc converges to AIC.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] If the assumption that the model is univariate and linear with normal residuals does not hold, then the formula for AICc will generally be different from the formula above.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For some models, the formula can be difficult to determine.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For every model that has AICc available, though, the formula for AICc is given by AIC plus terms that includes both *k* and *k*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In comparison, the formula for AIC includes *k* but not *k*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In other words, AIC is a first-order estimate (of the information loss), whereas AICc is a second-order estimate.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Further discussion of the formula, with examples of other assumptions, is given by Burnham & Anderson (2002, ch.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In particular, with other assumptions, bootstrap estimation of the formula is often feasible.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To summarize, AICc has the advantage of tending to be more accurate than AIC (especially for small samples), but AICc also has the disadvantage of sometimes being much more difficult to compute than AIC.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that if all the candidate models have the same *k* and the same formula for AICc, then AICc and AIC will give identical (relative) valuations; hence, there will be no disadvantage in using AIC, instead of AICc.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Furthermore, if *n* is many times larger than *k*2, then the extra penalty term will be negligible; hence, the disadvantage in using AIC, instead of AICc, will be negligible.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The Akaike information criterion was formulated by the statistician Hirotugu Akaike.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] It was originally named "an information criterion".
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] It was first announced in English by Akaike at a 1971 symposium; the proceedings of the symposium were published in 1973.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The 1973 publication, though, was only an informal presentation of the concepts.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The first formal publication was a 1974 paper by Akaike.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The initial derivation of AIC relied upon some strong assumptions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Takeuchi (1976) showed that the assumptions could be made much weaker.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Takeuchi's work, however, was in Japanese and was not widely known outside Japan for many years.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] AIC was originally proposed for linear regression (only) by Sugiura (1978).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] That instigated the work of Hurvich & Tsai (1989), and several further papers by the same authors, which extended the situations in which AICc could be applied.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The first general exposition of the information-theoretic approach was the volume by Burnham & Anderson (2002).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] It includes an English presentation of the work of Takeuchi.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The volume led to far greater use of AIC, and it now has more than 64,000 citations on Google Scholar.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Akaike called his approach an "entropy maximization principle", because the approach is founded on the concept of entropy in information theory.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Indeed, minimizing AIC in a statistical model is effectively equivalent to maximizing entropy in a thermodynamic system; in other words, the information-theoretic approach in statistics is essentially applying the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] As such, AIC has roots in the work of Ludwig Boltzmann on entropy.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For more on these issues, see Akaike (1985) and Burnham & Anderson (2002, ch.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A statistical model must account for random errors.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A straight line model might be formally described as *y**i* = *b*0 + *b*1*x**i* + *ε**i*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Here, the *ε**i* are the residuals from the straight line fit.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Gaussian (with zero mean), then the model has three parameters: *b*0, *b*1, and the variance of the Gaussian distributions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Thus, when calculating the AIC value of this model, we should use *k*=3.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] More generally, for any least squares model with i.i.d.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Gaussian residuals, the variance of the residuals' distributions should be counted as one of the parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] As another example, consider a first-order autoregressive model, defined by *x**i* = *c* + *φx**i*−1 + *ε**i*, with the *ε**i* being i.i.d.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For this model, there are three parameters: *c*, *φ*, and the variance of the *ε**i*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] More generally, a *p*th-order autoregressive model has *p* + 2 parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The AIC values of the candidate models must all be computed with the same data set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Sometimes, though, we might want to compare a model of the response variable, *y*, with a model of the logarithm of the response variable, log(*y*).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] More generally, we might want to compare a model of the data with a model of transformed data.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Following is an illustration of how to deal with data transforms (adapted from Burnham & Anderson (2002, §2.11.3): "Investigators should be sure that all hypotheses are modeled using the same response variable").
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Suppose that we want to compare two models: one with a normal distribution of *y* and one with a normal distribution of log(*y*).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We should *not* directly compare the AIC values of the two models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Instead, we should transform the normal cumulative distribution function to first take the logarithm of *y*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To do that, we need to perform the relevant integration by substitution: thus, we need to multiply by the derivative of the (natural) logarithm function, which is 1/*y*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] —which is the probability density function for the log-normal distribution.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] We then compare the AIC value of the normal model against the AIC value of the log-normal model.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] For misspecified model, Takeuchi's Information Criterion (TIC) might be more appropriate.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] However, TIC often suffers from instability caused by estimation errors.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Several alternative model selection criteria have been proposed and studied in statistical literature.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] These methods differ in their assumptions, asymptotic behavior, and suitability depending on the goals of the analysis — such as prediction, inference, or model interpretation.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A comprehensive overview of AIC and other model selection methods is given by Ding et al.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A critical difference between AIC and BIC (and their variants) lies in their asymptotic behavior under well-specified and misspecified model classes.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Their fundamental differences have been well-studied in regression variable selection and autoregression order selection problems.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In general, if the goal is prediction, AIC and leave-one-out cross-validations are preferred.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The formula for the Bayesian information criterion (BIC) is similar to the formula for AIC, but with a different penalty for the number of parameters.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] With AIC the penalty is 2*k*, whereas with BIC the penalty is ln(*n*)*k*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A comparison of AIC/AICc and BIC is given by Burnham & Anderson (2002, §6.3-6.4), with follow-up remarks by Burnham & Anderson (2004).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The authors show that AIC/AICc can be derived in the same Bayesian framework as BIC, just by using different prior probabilities.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In the Bayesian derivation of BIC, though, each candidate model has a prior probability of 1/*R* (where *R* is the number of candidate models).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Additionally, the authors present a few simulation studies that suggest AICc tends to have practical/performance advantages over BIC.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] A point made by several researchers is that AIC and BIC are appropriate for different tasks.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In particular, BIC is argued to be appropriate for selecting the "true model" (i.e. the process that generated the data) from the set of candidate models, whereas AIC is not appropriate.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] To be specific, if the "true model" is in the set of candidates, then BIC will select the "true model" with probability 1, as *n* → ∞; in contrast, when selection is done via AIC, the probability can be less than 1.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Proponents of AIC argue that this issue is negligible, because the "true model" is virtually never in the candidate set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Indeed, it is a common aphorism in statistics that "all models are wrong"; hence the "true model" (i.e. reality) cannot be in the candidate set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Another comparison of AIC and BIC is given by Vrieze (2012).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Vrieze presents a simulation study—which allows the "true model" to be in the candidate set (unlike with virtually all real data).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The simulation study demonstrates, in particular, that AIC sometimes selects a much better model than BIC even when the "true model" is in the candidate set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The reason is that, for finite *n*, BIC can have a substantial risk of selecting a very bad model from the candidate set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] This reason can arise even when *n* is much larger than *k*2.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] With AIC, the risk of selecting a very bad model is minimized.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] If the "true model" is not in the candidate set, then the most that we can hope to do is select the model that best approximates the "true model".
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] AIC is appropriate for finding the best approximating model, under certain assumptions.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Comparison of AIC and BIC in the context of regression is given by Yang (2005).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In regression, AIC is asymptotically optimal for selecting the model with the least mean squared error, under the assumption that the "true model" is not in the candidate set.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] BIC is not asymptotically optimal under the assumption.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Yang additionally shows that the rate at which AIC converges to the optimum is, in a certain sense, the best possible.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Sometimes, each candidate model assumes that the residuals are distributed according to independent identical normal distributions (with zero mean).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] That gives rise to least squares model fitting.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] where *C* is a constant independent of the model, and dependent only on the particular data points, i.e. it does not change if the data does not change.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Note that if all the models have the same *k*, then selecting the model with minimum AIC is equivalent to selecting the model with minimum RSS—which is the usual objective of model selection based on least squares.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Leave-one-out cross-validation is asymptotically equivalent to AIC, for ordinary linear regression models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Asymptotic equivalence to AIC also holds for mixed-effects models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Akaike stated, 'It is interesting to note that the use of a statistic proposed by Mallows is essentially equivalent to our present approach'.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] However, the precise relation between AIC and *Cp* requires some nuance.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] (I deliberately stop using ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ here to avoid confusion below).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] This final expression (neglecting terms with *n*) is Mallows' *Cp* when $\sigma ^{2}$ happens to be known.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In the more usual situation where this is unknown, an estimate ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ , typically derived from a model using all possible predictors, must be substituted.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] This leads to an asymptotic equivalence between AIC and *Cp*.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] However, Akaike noted that 'unfortunately some subjective judgement is required for the choice of ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ in the definition of *Cp*'.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] In the unusual case that $\sigma ^{2}$ is known, AIC is exactly equal to (**1**).
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] As a result, (**1**) is sometimes considered to be AIC, and AIC and *Cp* are claimed to be equivalent.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Such statements should be considered incorrect; when AIC is correctly implemented, the equivalence is only asymptotic.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Other model selection criteria include the Widely Applicable Information Criterion (WAIC) and the Deviance Information Criterion (DIC), both of which are widely used in Bayesian model selection.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] WAIC, in particular, is asymptotically equivalent to leave-one-out cross-validation and applies even in complex or singular models.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The Hannan–Quinn criterion (HQC) offers a middle ground between AIC and BIC by applying a lighter penalty than BIC but a heavier one than AIC.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] The Minimum Description Length (MDL) principle, closely related to BIC, approaches model selection from an information-theoretic perspective, treating it as a compression problem.
[src:aggregate-data/akaike-information-criterion] Each of these methods has advantages depending on model complexity, sample size, and the goal of analysis.
